			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">It's very rare you'll have a MMORPG with healing that doesn't rely on that class. Consider a boss encounter where you've got 5 people fighting a single monster. In order for that monster to be balanced ideally they'd be 5 times as strong as a single player. So you have a monster with 5 times the hit points that hits 5 times as hard (assuming all classes are balanced). In order to survive a group of say 5 mages would have to unload all their mana to kill him before any of them get killed. Now lets assume that this is possible, and the encounter is balanced with that in mind. Take the same group and replace a single mage with a healer. Now suddenly you aren't in danger of dying at all and the four mages with the single healer would suddenly find the encounter trivial. Add a tank and it only increases the ease of the encounter. 
<br />

<br />
I think of this as 'defense bias' in MMORPGs and I think it's fair to say that it's largely unavoidable, and also a good thing. MMORPGs tend to have a 'offensive bias' as well that makes the best DPS classes sought after as well, although they tend to be more popular so you don't run into problems as much finding them for groups. It would make the game significantly less challenging if they balanced encounters around the idea that the weakest formation was capable of everything, because it's inevitable that someone will form a group that isn't the weakest possible set up. On top of that their is something to be said about trying to encourage groups to be well balanced so that everyone is wanted in a group for different reasons. 
<br />

<br />
I think ideally you'd look for a game with only a small number of classes or at least a situation where you have clearly defined roles for each class and you required at least one of each role to form a balanced group. WoW hit the mark on this one in my opinion but they definitely do require healing classes and I've seen many people become frustrated with their inability to find a balanced group as a result. I guess I don't see this is a correctable issue for any game that intends to have group based content that isn't very easy. I don't think solo content will ever be the focus of MMORPGs and from your post I get the impression you're more interested in the social aspects of the genre which keeps you coming back. I'm just not sure the kind of game you're looking for would be successful for this genre.<br />_________________<br />()()
<br />
(^.^)
<br />
(''')(''')</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
