			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">As near as I can tell, this dependence on healers (and preferrably a tank class for them to heal) is necessary.  If you stick to the idea that players have hitpoints and they die at zero hitpoints, but there are clerics to heal those hitpoints, and dragons hit hard enough that you need some healing to survive... well, it becomes almost inevitable.  So we're stuck with it in pretty much every game for awhile.
<br />

<br />
What would it really take to get away from healer-dominated MMORPGs?
<br />

<br />
Idea 1:
<br />
In most games today clerics have at least enough healing per second to match the damage output of a mob.  If they couldn't heal that fast they'd be unable to keep a person alive.  HPS &gt;= DPS.  Imagine if HPS was much much lower than DPS, or in the extreme if there was no healing at all.  The only way to win a battle would be to spread the damage out to everyone in the group, there couldn't be one dedicated tank.  You'd just hope that you could kill the mob fast enough, before everyone's hitpoints were gone.
<br />

<br />
For practical reasons, that DPS would have to be pretty low.  For a 40 person raid to have a ten minute fight against a dragon, each and every person in the raid needs to tank the dragon for at least 20 seconds each -- in addition to any sort of AE damage that happens during the fight.  Or for a group of six to fight for 3 minutes each person has to tank the mob (or multiple mobs) for at least 30 seconds.  And if DPS is low, then HPS is even lower.  At that point it's actually usually better to get another warrior instead, so you can kill the mob faster.  Congrats, you made healers so weak that there useless.
<br />

<br />
Well, that's not completely true.  Only during-battle healing is made useless.  There could be all sorts of powerful healing and buffing between battles.  But that's another story.
<br />

<br />
Would such a game be exciting?  Maybe, but it would definitely seem 'slow', there would be hardly any twitch factor at all.  It would be more strategic.
<br />

<br />
Idea 2:
<br />
Clerics like to hit the heal button almost as often as offensive classes hit their attack buttons -- once every ten seconds at least, preferrably more.  It makes them feel involved in the battle.  So we get mobs that hit really hard and a huge amount of healing is needed.  With mobs hitting so hard, even tanks can't go more than ten seconds without a heal, and as a result groups in general can't accomplish anything without a healer.
<br />

<br />
Result: if clerics aren't the dominant class in a MMORPG then they're boring and nobody will want to play them.
<br />

<br />
Idea 3:
<br />
There IS another option, one which was actually used in EQ for awhile.  Have healing limited by mana rather than speed.  When the wizard gets aggro away from the warrior the group doesn't have to think 'oh no, the wizard is going to die quickly if the cleric doesn't react fast'.  Instead they think 'oh no, the cleric will run out of mana and need a med break because the wizard has weak armor'.  Personally, I liked that version of EQ, but I know the clerics complained about spending all their time meditating and doing little else.
<br />

<br />
That's fine and dandy for groups, if they don't fight efficiently they pay the price in downtime or sometimes even death.  But what about raids?  If mana, or mana efficiency, is the limit to what you can handle, then winning is a matter of doing enough DPS to the dragon to kill it before your clerics run out of mana.  Basically, you get those marathon Luclin fights that lasted an hour.
<br />

<br />
Excitement is also limited in this case.  Med breaks are not exciting.  And in raids you don't have the constant fear of death every few seconds.  Rather you have the clerics' mana gradually going down, at roughtly the same rate as the dragon's health goes down, and once you find the rhythm there's almost zero chance of anyone dying during the last 59 minutes of the fight.  You also get some less-than-heroic roles for some classes, such as mod-rod-dispenser or twitch-the-cleric.
<br />

<br />
So... it's not terribly surprising that in PoP and later EQ switched to more fast-paced healing and much higher-DPS mobs to make battles, and especially raids, more exciting.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
